{"title_page": "Marc Kramer", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name                = Marc Kramer\n| image               = Marc Kramer pic from Phila Inquirer.jpg\n| caption             = Mark Kramer\n\n}}\n\n'''Marc Kramer''' is an American serial entrepreneur, business book author and journalist. He founded the country's first formally organized investor angel network, the Pennsylvania Private Investors Group, now called the Private Investors Forum,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/print-edition/2012/10/19/the-difference-between-angel-investors.html |publisher=Philadelphia Business Journal |title= The Difference Between Angel Investors Here and Out West}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://medcitynews.com/2012/06/5-things-to-consider-before-you-pitch-at-a-venture-fair/ |publisher=Med City News |title= 5 Things To Consider Before You Pitch At A Venture Fair}}</ref> and the country's first cyber bank insurance product for small businesses, Commercial Deposit Insurance.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdiaus.com/images/asset_22.pdf |publisher= Philadelphia Business Journal |title= Philadelphia Business Journal-Marc Kramer Interview |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140108043022/https://www.cdiaus.com/images/asset_22.pdf |archivedate= 2014-01-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdiaus.com/images/asset_21.pdf |website= The Wall Street Journal |title= New Insurance Offers Cyber Bank Theft Protection to Small Business |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140108040716/https://www.cdiaus.com/images/asset_21.pdf |archivedate= 2014-01-08 }}</ref> Marc is also founder of Dads & Daughters, a group that made sure that entrepreneurial fathers and their daughters got together every Saturday for uninterrupted time.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://articles.philly.com/1995-06-22/news/25688716_1_daughters-fathers-dads |publisher=Philly.com |title= Play's The Thing For Daddies' Girls A Little Business And A Lot Of Bonding}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nMarc Kramer was born in [[Coatesville, Pennsylvania]], to Robert Kramer, a small business owner, and Shelly Kramer, a fine China sales representative for Macy's Department Store. Kramer graduated from Coatesville High School in 1978. He attended and graduated from [[West Virginia University]] [[Perley Isaac Reed School of Journalism]] in 1982<ref>{{cite web|url= http://alumni.wvu.edu/membership/spotlight/marc-kramer |publisher=WVU Alumni Magazine |title= WVU Grad Helping Small Businesses Fend Off Cyber Attacks}}</ref> and obtained a Master's in Management in 1991 from The [[Pennsylvania State University]].\n\n== Career ==\n\nKramer started his career as sports writer for the Village News and the Coatesville Record. He left sports writing in 1983 and joined Berkheimer Associates to become a tax administrator. While working for Berkheimer Associates, Kramer started a part-time marketing business called Kramer Marketing. His firm client, the Downingtown Marketplace, hired Kramer to be assistant manager in 1984.\n\nDuring his time at the Downingtown Marketplace, Kramer started the Downingtown Antique Hub, a small business center and a mirrored closet store business.  Kramer left the Downingtown Marketing place in 1987 to become the first executive director of the Penn State Technology Development Center in Great Valley, Pa, which he grew from one company to 53 and lead the nation in minority startup companies.\n\nIn 1990, Kramer left the Penn State Technology<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archives/article_4f0c1eb0-9b88-5dfa-8658-1780bd925cd0.html |publisher=The Daily Collegian |title= PSU Incubator Lends Success To Business}}</ref> to start the Eastern Technology Council, which was the second largest technology council in the United States.  During his time with ETC, he started the Pennsylvania Private Investors Group and a national newspaper, Technology Times.\n\nKramer started Kramer Communications, a marketing and new venture development consultancy in 1997. While running Kramer Communications, he started PA Artist Entrepreneur in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/webguide/internetlife/2003-10-02-artists-and-business_x.htm |website=USA Today |title= Web site aims to give artists lessons in business}}</ref> co-founded in 2003 with his then wife, Jacqueline Kramer, Expert Speakers,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2003/03/10/newscolumn1.html |publisher=Philadelphia Business Journal |title= Web Site Gives Groups Chance To Find Speakers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bizjournals.com/austin/stories/2007/07/09/story8.html |publisher=Austin Business Journal |title= Speakers Snaps Up Rival}}</ref> marketing business professionals to trade associations and corporations and was sold to Speaker Match in 2005, Prompt Payment, which provided reverse factoring service, in 2007, and Commercial Deposit Insurance,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.philly.com/philly/columnists/jeff_gelles/20130404_Fighting_cyber_crime_at_mid-sized_companies.html |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |title= CDIA Fighting Cyber Crime at Small Companies}}</ref> which insures small business bank accounts against cyber theft of funds, in 2012.\n\nKramer is the executive director of the Private Investors Forum and runs the  [http://digital.olivesoftware.com/Olive/ODN/PhiladelphiaInquirer/shared/ShowArticle.aspx?doc=PHQP%2F2017%2F03%2F05&entity=Ar05901&sk=57A6A445 Angel Venture Fair], which draws entrepreneurs from all over the world to present their business plans to angel investors.\n\nCurrently, Kramer is the executive director of the Angel Venture Fair,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.philly.com/philly/business/small_business/Phila-Angel-Venture-Fair-startups-Robin-Hood-Union-League.html|title= Angel Fair brings 'Shark Tank' vibe to Philly start-ups}}</ref> which brings together entrepreneurs and investors from around the world, and formerly Executive-in-Residence at [[Saint Joseph%27s University|Saint Joseph's University]] in Philadelphia, Pa.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://sites.sju.edu/ifbe/about-us-2/meet-our-team/marc-kramer/|title= The Initiative for Family Business & Entrepreneurship}}</ref>\n\nKramer has taught marketing, entrepreneurship, marketing, management and family business at the University of Pennsylvania Wharton School of Business, Temple University Fox School of Business, Drexel University LeBow School of Business, University of Louisville in Panama City, Panama, Universidad de Pacifico in Lima, Peru, Universidad de Los Andes, Bogota, Colombia, Rutgers University Rohrer College of Business at Rowan University.\n\n== Personal ==\n\nMarc Kramer was married to Jacqueline Kadoch, a Spanish interpreter for social service organizations, from 1984 to 2013. He has two daughters, Ariel Kramer, president of Klover Communications, and Sydney Kramer, author of Cookie Dalmatian Mysteries. Kramer also has two sisters, Dr. Randi Braman, a family doctor in Owings Mills, Maryland, and Leslie Kramer, vice president of Human Resources at First Bank of Perkosie.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* Nominated for [[Inc. (magazine)]] Entrepreneur of the Year award four times, 1988, 1990, 1991, and winning in 1991.\n* American Electronics Association Spirit of America Award in 1994.\n* Top 30 Business Books in 2000 by Executive Book Summaries.\n* Top 40 Under 40 Philadelphia Business Journal Business Leader in 1991\n* Philadelphia Jaycees Top Five Young Business Leaders in 1993, 1994 and 1995.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n=== Books ===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131207044621/http://sterlingandross.com/YYC.html Yes You Can: How to Become an Entrepreneur to Control Your Professional and Financial Future], Fall 2010, Sterling and Ross\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Consulting-Business-Generates-Dollars-Financial/dp/1891984977/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1388945814