s]].\n\nDuring the early 1980s, Gilles Dufour often took the teenage de Castellane out to famed Parisian nightclubs such as Le Palace<ref name=\"W\" /> where she first experimented with dressing up in playful, flamboyant and ultra-feminine styles, often sporting [[Mickey Mouse]] ears or a devil\u2019s horns headband<ref name=\"Vogue\" /> and wearing lingerie on the outside of her clothing.\n\n== Chanel (1984-1998) ==\n\nDe Castellane joined [[Chanel]] in 1984 where she started as a studio assistant. Creative director [[Karl Lagerfeld]] soon asked her to oversee the development of costume jewelry designs. Over the 14 years<ref name=\"Vogue\" /> she worked at [[Chanel]], de Castellane remained a vibrant inspiration for Lagerfeld, bringing her fashion playfulness to the costume jewelry, layering it with cartoon and pop-culture references.<ref name=\"Vogue\" />\n\nOf de Castellane, Lagerfeld commented, \"She follows the rules I like best in life: Don't compare. Don't compete. You look at her. You get the message.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1987/10/23/style/at-chanel-an-assistant-is-inspiration.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm \"At Chanel, An assistant, Is Inspiration\"], article by Michael Gross, ''[[The New York Times]]'', New York, 23 October 1987.</ref>\n\nDe Castellane sometimes appeared on the [[Chanel]] catwalk modelling the house's collections.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n== Dior Joaillerie (1998-present) ==\n\nIn January 1998, [[Bernard Arnault]], chairman and CEO of the world's largest luxury group [[LVMH]], announced the launch of the [[Christian Dior]] brand's inaugural jewelry division, Dior Joaillerie. In doing so he appointed Victoire de Castellane to become the Dior Fine Jewelry Creator.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nHer sources of inspiration include floral and natural motifs, as well as a global mix of pop culture, such as \"''Technicolor, [[Alice in Wonderland]], [[Manga]] characters, the [[Brothers Grimm]], [[Walt Disney Pictures]], Venus Flytraps, Bassett\u2019s Liquorice allsorts, the visual excesses of Bollywood and the darkest depths of the subconscious.<ref name=\"W\" />''\"\n\nPieces from Dior Joaillerie's ''Belladone Island'' collection were premiered on January 12, 2007 on the online virtual world Second Life. The entire collection was subsequently presented on February 27 in an exhibition in Monet's Water Lilies room at the Mus\u00e9e de l'Orangerie in [[Paris]].<ref name=\"Vogue\" />\n\nEach year de Castellane creates a High Jewelry collection and at least one Fine Jewelry collection for Dior Joaillerie, as well as numerous one-off, bespoke pieces for individual clients.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nIn 2009 de Castellane marked her 10th anniversary at Dior Joaillerie with the ''Rois et Reines'' collection. Each of the 20 pieces \u2013 10 kings and 10 queens \u2013 featured a three-dimensional skull carved from ornamental and often translucent stones such as chrysolite, chalcedony and jade, then dressed in diamond-encrusted collars and crowns.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nIn 2018 Dior reveals Victoire de Castellane's  High Jewellery collections in a retrospective organized according to three of Christian Dior's favorite themes: couture, formal balls and gardens, displayed at the Mus\u00e9e d\u2019Art Moderne in Paris.  Among these treasures, visitors discover creations from the new Dior Dior Dior collection, an homage to lace and to haute couture. \n\nIn 2019, on the occasion of Dior Joaillerie's 20th anniversary, journalist [https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo%C3%AFc_Prigent Lo\u00efc Prigent] unveils a unique retrospective of the collections imagined by [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tEWRHLv2ckI&t=357s Victoire de Castellane]. \n\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\nIn March 2011, de Castellane had her first solo exhibition of personal work at Gagosian Gallery in Paris.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\nEntitled ''Fleur d\u2019exc\u00e8s'', the show featured a collection of ten one-off pieces with faux-classificatory monikers such as L. Es Delirium Flash, Quo Ca\u00efnus Magic Disco and Hero\u00efna Romanticam Dolorosa.\n\nIn January and March 2014 \"Animalvegetablemineral\" the second personal exhibition of unique object by Victoire de Castellane is presented at Gagosian Gallery Davies Street, London & Gagosian Madison Avenue, New York.\n\n\"Victoire de Castellane has heard the cry of Mother Nature once again, with a new art-meets-precious-jewelry collection that features moonlight snakes, ultra bright flower blossoms and clusters of flat diamonds meant to mimic water. Her first London show,  'Animalvegetablemineral', opens today at Gagosian Gallery on Davies street in Mayfair, and run through saturday. Next month, it moves to Gagosian on Madison Avenue in New York, where it will be open from March 12 to April 5. Animalvegetablemineral' builds on Fleurs d'exc\u00e8s, de Castellane's collection of undulating, sculptural jewels also inspired by the natural world, which made its debut in Paris in 2011.\"\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nVictoire de Castellane lives in Paris with her husband Thomas Lenthal, the art director and founder of ''Paradis'' magazine. She has three children from a previous marriage with Paul-Emmanuel Reiffers and a daughter with Lenthal.\n\n== Awards, distinctions and popular culture references ==\n*2009 de Castellane received the Fashion Award at The Fashion Group International's 26th annual \"Night Of Stars\"{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n*2012 de Castellane had a minor role in Sofia Coppola's 2006 film Marie Antoinette.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n*2007 de Castellane was awarded the L\u00e9gion d\u2019Honneur in February 2007.\n*2015 de Castellane received the Visionaries Award by the Museum of Arts and Design of New York{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n== Notes ==\n* [http://www.wmagazine.com/accessories/2011/03/victoire_de_castellane Wmagazine.com March 2011, article by Jonathan Wingfield ]\n* [http://gagosian.cdn.crvncms.com/__data/ef965000ef24fe19a771ab36fd7e1ec2.pdf Vogue May 2012, article by Hamish Bowles]\n* [http://www.gagosian.com/artists/victoire-de-castellane Victoire de Castellane \u2013 Gagosian Gallery]\n* [http://www.dior.com Dior.com site internet officiel]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* ''Dior Joaillerie''. Rizzoli (2012)\n* ''Victoire de Castellane, Fleurs d\u2019exc\u00e8s''. Galerie Gagosian Paris (2011)\n* ''Belladone Island''. Steidl (2007)\n* [[Judith Thurman]] [http://www.newyorker.com/talk/2014/03/31/140331ta_talk_thurman \"Stoner\"] in [[The New Yorker]], 31 March 2014 Issue\n* Carine Bizet [http://victoiredecastellane.com/press/press-animalvegetablemineral/le-monde-april-2014/page-1-3-158 \"Le bijou est une extension de soi\"], Le Monde, 31 March 2014 Issue\n* Lo\u00efc Prigent, [http://victoiredecastellane.com/press/press-victoire-de-castellane/vanity-fair-france-october-2014/page-1-12-221 \"Mademeoiselle Bijoux\"], Vanity Fair France, October 2014\n* Marion Vignal,\"Dr\u00f4le de joailli\u00e8re\",[http://victoiredecastellane.com/press/press-victoire-de-castellane/elle-france-november-2015/-bfdce6eb-26b4-4bd0-9223-784b0961b41c], Elle France, November 2015\n* Marion Hume, [http://victoiredecastellane.com/press/press-victoire-de-castellane/the-australian-financial-review-magazine-december-2015/-269c6b42-7e1a-4670-81fe-78ee5d9e20dd \"Queen of the desert\"], The Australian Financial Review Magazine, December 2015\n* Alice Edwards, [http://victoiredecastellane.com/press/press-victoire-de-castellane/sunday-times-style-february-2017/-917fe970-3ad4-4102-9214-f27ad729c4dd \"Romancing the stones\"], Sunday Times Style, February 2017\n* Museum of Modern Art, [https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x630upy Jewellery in the eye of Victoire de Castellane] as a part of Medusa ... \n* Nathalie Azoulai (text) and Victoire de Castellane (illustrations) : [https://www.albin-michel.fr/ouvrages/jaime-pas-me